04184nam a22004815i 9780300167429DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20112011ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001674297 a10.12987/97803001674292doi  a(DE-B1597)486098  a(OCoLC)808346459  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 7aHIS0540002bisacsh1 aHarline, Craig, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSunday :bA History of the First Day from Babylonia to the Super Bowl /cCraig Harline. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (480 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface to The Paperback Edition -- tA Word Before: Super Bowl Sunday, Recently -- t1. Sunday Ascendant: Origins to AD 800 -- t2. Sunday Middle-Aged: A English Village in 1300, in June, When the Sun Was Soft* -- t3. Sunday Reformed: A Dutch Town in 1624, in Winter, When the Sun Was Low -- t4. Sunday À La Mode: Paris in the 1890s, in Mid-Spring -- t5. Sunday Obscured: Belgium, August 2, 1914 -- t6. Sunday Still: England Between Wars -- t7. Sunday All Mixed Up: The United States in the 1950s -- tA Word After: Asse, Belgium, the Annual Kiwanis Barbecue -- tBibliographical Notes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe mere mention of "Sunday" will immediately conjure up a rich mix of memories, associations, and ideas for most anyone of any age. Whatever we think of-be it attending church, reading a bulky newspaper, eating brunch, or watching football-Sunday occupies a unique place in Western civilization. But how did we come to have a day with such a singular set of traditions? Here, historian Craig Harline examines Sunday from its ancient beginnings to contemporary America in a fascinating blend of stories and analysis. For the earliest Christians, the first day of the week was a time to celebrate the liturgy, observe the Resurrection, and work. But over time, Sunday in the Western world took on still other meanings and rituals, especially in the addition of both rest and recreation to the day's activities. Harline illuminates these changes in enlightening profiles of Sunday in medieval Catholic England, Sunday in the Reformation, and Sunday in nineteenth-century France-home of the most envied and sometimes despised Sunday of the modern world. He continues with moving portraits of soldiers and civilians trying to observe Sunday during World War I, examines the quiet Sunday of England in the 1930s, and concludes with the convergence of various European traditions in the American Sunday, which also adds some distinctly original habits of its own, such as in the realms of commerce and professional sports.With engaging prose and scholarly integrity, Sunday is an entertaining and long-overdue look at a significant hallmark of Western culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300167429423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300167429.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles